  "summary": "Hercule Poirot arrives at a Gothic riverside house to meet Alistair Brent, a wealthy banker. During the meeting in the study, Alistair is joined by his wife's niece, Mrs. Olivia, who is complaining to him. Jane Olivia, Alistair's great-niece, reveals that her motive for summoning Poirot is to discuss the disappearance of Sainsbury Silas. As part of the conversation, Jane recounts an encounter from three months prior: while Alistair was traveling in a Rolls Royce, they stopped at 58 Charlotte Street, where a middle-aged woman in artistic clothing approached him claiming to be a friend of his wife, Rebecca. Although Alistair does not remember her, Jane suggests the woman was merely soliciting donations for the Zenana Missions.\n\nFollowing the meeting, Jane pulls Poirot aside for a private confrontation. Poirot reveals that he knows she actually summoned him to persuade him to discuss a dentist named Howard Lix. He further challenges Jane regarding her suspicious reaction to the murder of the dentist Mr. Morley and her connection to a young American named Howard Roxter. Jane admits she was attempting to mislead him and confesses her infatuation with Roxter. She explains her family's internal conflicts, noting that her mother seeks to secure Alistair's inheritance and that Jane finds Alistair's conservative, old-fashioned values to be in direct conflict with the radical views held by Howard Roxter.",
